                    </div>
                    <span>This is the most touching and beautiful story I have ever read. I am grateful to Ralph Helfer for telling it. I would recommend the book to everyone.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Modoc -- My guess: Part accurate, part invention</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-04-05</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Many reviewers have commented on the obvious non-factuality of Modoc -- the lack of tusks in the illustrations, the fact that the pictures seem to be of two elephants. To me, all seemed well until India hove into sight. I have been around India a lot. Most of what was written about it in Modoc seems vastly unlikely. Girl-boy relations in India are not like that. Refusal of a dowry would have been a massive insult. How come bandits and hill tribes all spoke English? And to a German! There was no "People's Liberation Army" in India before 1940. Biplanes with machine guns in India then? And on and on. Moving to the USA, I can't see, as a doctor myself, what insect poison could be produced in copious enough quantities to poison even one elephant, let alone dozens. And there would be no "vaccine" (actually, antidote) to any such agent. A highly romanced tale, at best. Like almost all reviewers, though, I found some good philosophy in the book, a natural wisdom, and a great insight into the relationship between humans and animals. When the author is in his elephant, sorry "element", namely animal training, then he seems truly authentic. Thanks for writing it, anyway, Ralph.</span>
                  
              
